Six congruent copies of the parabola $y = x^2$ are arranged in the plane so that each vertex is tangent to a circle, and each parabola is tangent to its two neighbors.  Find the radius of the circle.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return (x^2 + 3/4);
}

path parab = graph(func,-1.5,1.5);

draw(parab);
draw(rotate(60)*(parab));
draw(rotate(120)*(parab));
draw(rotate(180)*(parab));
draw(rotate(240)*(parab));
draw(rotate(300)*(parab));
draw(Circle((0,0),3/4));
[/asy]

inference:
Let the circle have radius $r.$  Let the vertex of one parabola be at $(0,r),$ and let the point of tangency of this parabola with the circle be $(r,r).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return (x^2 + 3/4);
}

path parab = graph(func,-1.5,1.5);

draw(parab);
draw(rotate(60)*(parab));
draw(rotate(120)*(parab));
draw(rotate(180)*(parab));
draw(rotate(240)*(parab));
draw(rotate(300)*(parab));
draw(Circle((0,0),3/4));
draw((0,3/4)--(3/4,3/4));
draw((0,0)--(3/4,3/4),dashed);
draw((0,3/4)--(0,0),dashed);
label("$r$", (3/8,3/8), NE);
label("$r$", (0,3/8), W);
[/asy]

Then the equation of the parabola is
\[y - r = (x - r)^2.\]Since $(r,r)$ lies on the parabola,
\[r - r = (r - r)^2,\]so this equation is satisfied.  The slope of the tangent line at $(r,r)$ is $2(r - r) = 0,$ so the tangent line is horizontal.  This means the center of the circle is directly below the vertex of the parabola, so the distance from the vertex to the center of the circle is $r.$

Thus, the distance from the vertex of the parabola to the point of tangency with the circle is $\sqrt{r^2 + r^2} = r \sqrt{2}.$  This means the distance from the vertex of one parabola to the vertex of the next parabola is $2r \sqrt{2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return (x^2 + 3/4);
}

path parab = graph(func,-1.5,1.5);

draw(parab);
draw(rotate(60)*(parab));
draw(rotate(120)*(parab));
draw(rotate(180)*(parab));
draw(rotate(240)*(parab));
draw(rotate(300)*(parab));
draw(Circle((0,0),3/4));
draw((0,3/4)--(3/4,3/4));
draw((0,0)--(3/4,3/4),dashed);
draw((0,3/4)--(0,0),dashed);
label("$r$", (3/8,3/8), NE);
label("$r$", (0,3/8), W);
draw((0,3/4)--(sqrt(3)/2 + 3/4,3/4),dashed);
label("$2r \sqrt{2}$", (sqrt(3)/4 + 3/8, 3/4), S);
[/asy]

The distance between the vertices of two consecutive parabolas is also $2r.$  Thus,
\[2r \sqrt{2} = 2r.\]Then $\sqrt{2} = 1,$ which is impossible.  This means there is no such circle.  In other words, the radius of the circle is $\boxed{\text{undefined}}.$

ground_truth:
Let $r$ be the radius of the circle.  Then we can assume that the graph of one of the parabolas is $y = x^2 + r.$

Since $\tan 60^\circ = \sqrt{3},$ the parabola $y = x^2 + r$ will be tangent to the line $y = x \sqrt{3}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return (x^2 + 3/4);
}

path parab = graph(func,-1.5,1.5);

draw(dir(240)--3*dir(60),red);
draw(parab);
draw(Circle((0,0),3/4));
draw((-2,0)--(2,0));

label("$60^\circ$", 0.5*dir(30));

dot((0,0),red);
[/asy]

This means the equation $x^2 + r = x \sqrt{3},$ or $x^2 - x \sqrt{3} + r = 0$ will have exactly one solution.  Hence, the discriminant will be 0, so $3 - 4r = 0,$ or $r = \boxed{\frac{3}{4}}.$

